<subSubSection lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="102" pageId="16" pageNumber="101" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="16.[189,310,747,773]" box="[189,310,747,773]" pageId="16" pageNumber="101">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,747,773]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="16" pageNumber="101" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,747,773]" pageId="16" pageNumber="101">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[188,1398,794,997]" pageId="16" pageNumber="101">Nine supralabials, the sixth or the fifth and sixth in contact with the eye; 10–11 infralabials; suboculars absent; 188–200 ventral scales; 84–103 subcaudal scales; tail 21 to 26% of the total length; maxillary teeth 10+3. A pale vertebral line three rows of scales wide is in contact with the parietal region, bordered by a pair of dorsolateral lines brown in color, five rows of scales wide extending from the temporal region to the tip of the tail. At about midbody the lateral line gives rise to a thinner lateral line that is one row of scales wide.</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5514561" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5514561" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5514561/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="101" startId="16.[189,232,1929,1955]" targetBox="[189,1398,1042,1897]" targetPageId="16">
<paragraph blockId="16.[189,1399,1929,2027]" pageId="16" pageNumber="101">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,269,1929,1955]" pageId="16" pageNumber="101">Fig. 9.</emphasis>
Locality records of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Cope, 1866)" baseAuthorityName="Cope" baseAuthorityYear="1866" box="[517,925,1929,1956]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Salvadoraceae" genus="Salvadora" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="16" pageNumber="101" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hexalepis">
<emphasis box="[517,758,1929,1955]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="101">Salvadora hexalepis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Cope E. D." box="[776,916,1929,1956]" pageId="16" pageNumber="101" pagination="300 - 314" refId="ref12468" refString="Cope E. D. 1866. On the Reptilia and Batrachia of the Sonoran Province of the Nearctic region. Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia 18: 300 - 314." type="journal article" year="1866">Cope, 1866</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and its subspecies. Blue dots represent 
<emphasis box="[189,378,1964,1991]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="101">S. h. mojavensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Bogert C. M." box="[386,543,1964,1991]" pageId="16" pageNumber="101" pagination="1 - 14" refId="ref12352" refString="Bogert C. M. 1945. Two additional races of the patch-nosed snake Salvadora hexalepis. American Museum Novitates 1285: 1 - 14." type="journal article" year="1945">Bogert, 1945</bibRefCitation>
; yellow dots 
<emphasis box="[700,864,1964,1991]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="101">S. h. virgultea</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Bogert C. M." box="[871,1028,1964,1991]" pageId="16" pageNumber="101" pagination="88 - 94" refId="ref12238" refString="Bogert C. M. 1935. Salvadora grahamiae virgultea, a new subspecies of the patch-nosed snake. Bulletin of the Southern California Academy of Sciences 34: 88 - 94." type="journal article" year="1935">Bogert, 1935</bibRefCitation>
; red dots 
<emphasis box="[1142,1193,1964,1991]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="101">S. h.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="(Cope, 1866)" baseAuthorityName="Cope" baseAuthorityYear="1866" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Salvadoraceae" genus="Salvadora" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="16" pageNumber="101" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hexalepis">
<emphasis box="[1201,1312,1964,1990]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="101">hexalepis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Cope E. D." pageId="16" pageNumber="101" pagination="300 - 314" refId="ref12468" refString="Cope E. D. 1866. On the Reptilia and Batrachia of the Sonoran Province of the Nearctic region. Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia 18: 300 - 314." type="journal article" year="1866">Cope, 1866</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and green dots 
<emphasis box="[443,600,2000,2026]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="101">S. h. klauberi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Bogert C. M." box="[607,763,1999,2026]" pageId="16" pageNumber="101" pagination="1 - 14" refId="ref12352" refString="Bogert C. M. 1945. Two additional races of the patch-nosed snake Salvadora hexalepis. American Museum Novitates 1285: 1 - 14." type="journal article" year="1945">Bogert, 1945</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="17.[188,1398,265,464]" pageId="17" pageNumber="102">
<emphasis box="[189,448,265,291]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="102">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Baird &amp; Girard" authorityYear="1853" box="[189,310,265,291]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Salvadoraceae" genus="Salvadora" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="17" pageNumber="102" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Salvadora</taxonomicName>
h. klauberi
</emphasis>
differs in having 12 + 3 maxillary teeth; in 
<emphasis box="[968,1160,265,291]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="102">S. h. mojavensis</emphasis>
suboculars separate the supralabials from the lower edge of the eye; 
<emphasis box="[749,918,299,326]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="102">
S. h. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Cope" baseAuthorityYear="1866" box="[807,918,299,325]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Salvadoraceae" genus="Salvadora" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="17" pageNumber="102" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hexalepis">hexalepis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
sometimes also lacks suboculars and has a single supralabial in contact with the eye similar to 
<emphasis box="[815,979,334,360]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="102">S. h. virgultea</emphasis>
, but it differs in its color pattern (in 
<emphasis box="[189,356,368,395]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="102">S. h. virgultea</emphasis>
the vertebral line involves three scale rows; the head is brown, and a lateral line is not distinguishable). In 
<emphasis box="[423,593,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="102">
S. h. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Cope" baseAuthorityYear="1866" box="[482,593,403,429]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Salvadoraceae" genus="Salvadora" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="17" pageNumber="102" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hexalepis">hexalepis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
the vertebral line is up to five scale rows wide; the head is gray; and the lateral line at midbody is completely separated from the dorsolateral line.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[189,1357,502,575]" pageId="17" pageNumber="102" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="17.[189,324,502,528]" box="[189,324,502,528]" pageId="17" pageNumber="102">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,502,528]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="17" pageNumber="102" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,502,528]" pageId="17" pageNumber="102">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[189,1357,548,575]" box="[189,1357,548,575]" pageId="17" pageNumber="102">
From the Latin ‘ 
<emphasis box="[382,485,548,574]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="102">virgultus</emphasis>
’, meaning ‘covered with scrub’, for the habitat in which the taxon occurs.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
